export const VOLUMES = {"I":{"title":"The Japanese table, restraint and one clean accent","intro":"Japanese cuisine plates colour with restraint — the pale of rice and tofu, the dark of nori and soy, lacquer black, and one clean accent of salmon, matcha, or pickle. The palette is quiet, fresh, and precise. Each refuses the over-bright 'sushi platter' cliché: real Japanese plating is mostly muted, with colour used sparingly and exactly."},"II":{"title":"The Italian table, tomato, basil, and flour","intro":"Italian food is built on a few vivid ingredients — tomato red, basil green, the cream of mozzarella and flour, olive-oil gold — against terracotta and marble. The palette is warm, fresh, and confident. Each refuses the muddy 'red-sauce' brown: real Italian colour is bright tomato and basil, not a heavy gravy."},"III":{"title":"The Mexican table, chilli, corn, and lime","intro":"Mexican food is a riot of grounded colour — chilli reds and browns, corn yellow, lime and cilantro green, and the deep mahogany of mole — on painted talavera and clay. The palette is warm, earthy, and bright. Each refuses the cheap 'Tex-Mex orange' cliché: real Mexican colour is complex chilli, deep mole, and fresh lime, not neon cheese."},"IV":{"title":"The Indian table, turmeric, chilli, and spice","intro":"Indian food is the most saturated cuisine of all — turmeric gold, chilli red, the green of coriander and mint, and the deep brown of garam masala — set on steel thalis and banana leaf. The palette is hot, layered, and joyful. Each refuses a flat 'curry brown': real Indian colour is a spectrum of distinct spice hues, not a single gravy."},"V":{"title":"The pâtisserie, pastel, glaze, and gold","intro":"French pâtisserie is refined pastel and glaze — macaron tints, the gold of butter pastry, glossy fruit glaçage, and chocolate's deep brown — on marble and porcelain. The palette is elegant and confectionery-soft. Each refuses garish bakery brights: the pâtisserie palette is muted pastel and warm gold, precise and restrained."},"VI":{"title":"The Nordic table, forage, sea, and rye","intro":"New Nordic cuisine plates the cold landscape — foraged green, sea grey-blue, rye and birch brown, and the dark of squid ink and berries — on rough ceramic and slate. The palette is muted, natural, and restrained. Each refuses bright restaurant colour: the Nordic plate is earthy, foraged, and quiet, with one berry or flower as accent."},"VII":{"title":"The mezze table, herb, sumac, and pomegranate","intro":"Levantine cooking is fresh green herb, creamy beige tahini and hummus, the deep red of sumac and pomegranate, and the gold of olive oil and saffron — on copper and ceramic. The palette is warm, herbal, and jewel-accented. Each refuses a flat 'hummus beige': the mezze table is bright with herb green, sumac red, and pomegranate ruby."},"VIII":{"title":"The Southeast-Asian table, lime, chilli, and herb","intro":"Southeast-Asian cooking is electric fresh colour — lime green, chilli red, the purple of shallot and the gold of curry — against banana leaf and the neon of a night market. The palette is bright, sharp, and herbaceous. Each refuses a muddy 'stir-fry brown': this is a cuisine of vivid lime, chilli, and herb, lit by market neon."},"IX":{"title":"The American table, griddle, smoke, and neon","intro":"American diner and barbecue food is warm and indulgent — griddle browns, ketchup-and-mustard primaries, pie golds, and the deep mahogany of smoked meat — under chrome and neon. The palette is hearty and nostalgic. Each refuses a greasy single brown: this is a cuisine of ketchup red, mustard yellow, pie gold, and smoke, with chrome shine."},"X":{"title":"The Chinese table, lacquer red, soy, and tea","intro":"Chinese cuisine ranges from the lacquer-red and gold of a banquet to the chilli-and-Sichuan-pepper red of the west and the pale steam of dim sum. The palette is warm, varied by region, and accented with soy-dark and scallion-green. Each refuses a single 'takeaway brown': real Chinese colour is lacquer red, chilli, jade, and tea, region by region."},"XI":{"title":"The sweet shop, chocolate, berry, and sugar","intro":"The dessert palette is indulgent and tactile — chocolate browns, berry brights, candy pastels, and caramel gold — glossy and rich. The colour is appetite itself. Each refuses a dull beige sweetness: dessert colour is deep chocolate, vivid berry, and glossy caramel, full of contrast."},"XII":{"title":"The glass and the cup, crema, ruby, and amber","intro":"Drinks have their own colour grammar — espresso's crema browns, wine's ruby-to-gold, whisky amber, and the jewel tones of cocktails. The palette is liquid, translucent, and warm. Each refuses a flat 'beverage brown': from crema to claret to chartreuse, drink colour is a rich translucent spectrum."}};
